3 means a child who is under the age of eighteen years and who:
4 (i) Except as provided in sections 43-1411 and 43-1414, was born out
5 of wedlock; or
6 (ii) Has been adopted by a second adult person under subdivision (1)
7 (c) of section 43-101;
8 (b) Child born out of wedlock means a child whose parents were not
9 married to each other at the time of birth, except that a child shall not
10 be considered as born out of wedlock if the parents were married at the
11 time of the child's conception but divorced at the time of birth. The
12 definition of legitimacy or illegitimacy for other purposes shall not be
13 affected by sections 43-1401 to 43-1418; and
14 (c) Support includes reasonable education.
15 (2) The changes made to this section by Laws 2025, LB150, apply to
16 actions under sections 43-1401 to 43-1418 that are pending on June 5,
17 2025, and to cases filed on or after such date.
18 Sec. 11. Section 43-1402, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
19 amended to read:
20 43-1402 The father of a child whose paternity is established either
21 by judicial proceedings or by acknowledgment as hereinafter provided
22 shall be liable for the child's its support to the same extent and in the
23 same manner as the father of a child born in lawful wedlock is liable for
24 the child's its support. The mother of a child shall also be liable for
25 the child's its support. Both parents of a child adopted by a second
26 adult person under subdivision (1)(c) of section 43-101 shall be liable
27 for the child's support. The liability of each parent may be determined,
28 enforced, and discharged in accordance with the methods hereinafter
29 provided.
30 Sec. 12. Section 43-1404, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
31 amended to read:
-17-

LB70 LB70
2026 2026
1 43-1404 The liability of the parent for support father or mother of
2 a child for its support shall be discharged by compliance with the terms
3 of a judicial decree for support or the terms of a judicially approved
4 settlement or by the adoption of the child by some other person or
5 persons.
6 Sec. 13. Section 43-1405, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
7 amended to read:
8 43-1405 (1) A settlement provided for in section 43-1404 means a
9 voluntary agreement:
10 (a) That is between:
11 (i) The the father of the child and the mother or some person
12 authorized to act in her behalf; ,
13 (ii) The or between the father and the next friend or guardian of
14 the child; ,
15 (iii) A parent of a child adopted by a second adult person under
16 subdivision (1)(c) of section 43-101 and the other such parent or some
17 person authorized to act in such other parent's behalf; or
18 (iv) A parent of a child adopted by a second adult person under
19 subdivision (1)(c) of section 43-101 and the next friend or guardian of
20 the child; and
21 (b) Whereby whereby the father or parent promises to make adequate
22 provision for the support of the child.
23 (2) In the event that such a settlement is made it shall be binding
24 on all parties and shall bar all other remedies of the mother and child,
25 any other parent, and the legal representatives of the child so long as
26 the settlement is it shall be performed by the parent promising to
27 provide support father, if such said settlement is approved by the court
28 having jurisdiction to compel the support of the child.
29 (3) The court shall approve such settlement only if the court finds
30 and determines it shall find and determine that adequate provision is
31 made for the support of the child and that the promising parent has
-18-

LB70 LB70
2026 2026
1 father shall have offered clear evidence of his willingness and ability
2 to perform the agreement. The court, in its discretion, may require the
3 promising parent father to furnish bond with proper sureties conditioned
4 upon the performance of the settlement.
5 Sec. 14. Section 43-1410, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska, is
6 amended to read:
7 43-1410 Any judicially approved settlement or order of support made
8 by a court having jurisdiction in the premises shall be binding on the
9 legal representatives of the parent father or mother in the event of his
10 or her death, to the same extent as other contractual obligations and
11 judicial judgments or decrees.
12 Sec. 15. Section 43-2924, Revised Statutes Cumulative Supplement,
13 2024, is amended to read:
14 43-2924 (1) The Parenting Act shall apply to proceedings or
15 modifications filed on or after January 1, 2008, in which parenting
16 functions for a child are at issue:
17 (a) Under under Chapter 42, including, but not limited to,
18 proceedings or modification of orders for dissolution of marriage and
19 child custody; and
20 (b) Under under sections 43-1401 to 43-1418; and .
21 (c) In a dispute between parents of a child adopted by a second
22 adult person under subdivision (1)(c) of section 43-101.
23 (2) The Parenting Act may apply to proceedings or modifications in
24 which parenting functions for a child are at issue under Chapter 30 or
25 43.
26 (3) The Parenting Act shall also apply to subsequent modifications
27 of bridge orders entered under section 43-246.02 by a separate juvenile
28 court or county court sitting as a juvenile court and docketed in a
29 district court.
30 (4) (2) The Parenting Act does not apply in any action filed by a
31 county attorney or authorized attorney pursuant to his or her duties
-19-

LB70 LB70
2026 2026
1 under section 42-358, 43-512 to 43-512.18, or 43-1401 to 43-1418, the
2 Income Withholding for Child Support Act, the Revised Uniform Reciprocal
3 Enforcement of Support Act before January 1, 1994, or the Uniform
4 Interstate Family Support Act for purposes of the establishment of
5 paternity and the establishment and enforcement of child and medical
6 support or a bridge order entered under section 43-246.02 by a separate
7 juvenile court or county court sitting as a juvenile court and docketed
8 in a district court. A county attorney or authorized attorney shall not
9 participate in the development of or court review of a parenting plan
10 under the Parenting Act. If both parents are parties to a paternity or
11 support action filed by a county attorney or authorized attorney, the
12 parents may proceed with a parenting plan.
13 Sec. 16. Original sections 43-104.15, 43-107, 43-512.04, 43-1402,
14 43-1404, 43-1405, and 43-1410, Reissue Revised Statutes of Nebraska,
15 sections 43-101, 43-101.01, 43-102, 43-104, 43-104.08, 43-104.13, and
16 43-2924, Revised Statutes Cumulative Supplement, 2024, and section
17 43-1401, Revised Statutes Supplement, 2025, are repealed.
